Step 1 — Dump LDAP data
mkdir -p ldapdomaindump-output && ldapdomaindump -u 'DOMAIN NAME\administrator' -p 'Password123!' -o ldapdomaindump-output 00.2.00
Step 2 — Open HTML report
xdg-open ldapdomaindump-output/index.html
Step 3 — Search for high-value terms
grep -RiE "Domain Admins|Enterprise Admins|DNSAdmins|svc|backup|sql" ldapdomaindump-output
Step 4 — Note interesting users / groups / hosts

Examples:

Service accounts

Domain admins

Server naming conventions

Privileged groups

Admin-accessible systems

Step 5 — Move into deeper tools

After this, I normally pivot into:

bloodhound-python

netexec ldap

netexec smb

rpcclient

enum4linux-ng

Manual LDAP searches if needed

Example Follow-Up Tools After ldapdomaindump
BloodHound collection
bloodhound-python -u administrator -p 'Password123!' -d DOMAIN NAME.local -ns 00.2.00 -c All
NetExec LDAP enum
nxc ldap 00.2.00 -u administrator -p 'Password123!'
NetExec SMB enum
nxc smb 00.2.00 -u administrator -p 'Password123!'
Common Errors / Troubleshooting
Invalid credentials / bind failed

If the tool fails to authenticate:

Re-check username format

Try DOMAIN\user

Try user@domain

Verify password

Confirm DC IP is correct

Port 389 closed / filtered

If LDAP port is blocked:

nmap -Pn -p 389,636 00.2.00
DNS or domain mismatch

If the domain is not resolving correctly:

Verify /etc/hosts if needed

Confirm the DC is actually the correct LDAP server

Check if you’re using the right domain name (DOMAIN NAME.local vs DOMAIN NAME.local)

Time skew issues

Sometimes AD auth gets weird if the attacker VM time is badly off:

date
Notes for GitHub (Safe Version)

For GitHub/public notes:

Replace real passwords with placeholders

Keep the domain as a lab domain

Avoid posting anything from a real environment

Do not upload actual dumped JSON/HTML from a live target

Screenshot only lab-safe data

Example public-safe command:

ldapdomaindump -u 'LAB\\user' -p 'SuperSecretPassword!' -o ldapdomaindump-output 00.2.00

Even better:

ldapdomaindump -u 'LAB\\user' -p '<REDACTED_PASSWORD>' -o ldapdomaindump-output 00.2.00
